{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4a103107-1795-4727-8758-3f91beb031e8","content":"PID 12345 isn't running on this machine, but here's how to diagnose and configure everything on your target system:\n\n---\n\n### Step 1 — Identify the Runtime\n\n```bash\n# If CoreCLR, you'll see libcoreclr.so in the loaded libraries:\ncat /proc/12345/maps | grep -q libcoreclr && echo \"CoreCLR\" || echo \"Likely NativeAOT\"\n\n# Alternative: check if the binary is self-contained (NativeAOT has no deps on libcoreclr)\nldd /proc/12345/exe | grep -i coreclr\n```\n\n- **CoreCLR** → `libcoreclr.so` will appear in the process memory maps.\n- **NativeAOT** → no managed runtime libraries; the binary is fully self-contained.\n\n---\n\n### Step 2 — Configure Crash Dumps\n\n#### If **CoreCLR**:\n\nThe runtime has built-in dump support via environment variables:\n\n```bash\n# Set these before launching the app (e.g. in a systemd unit or wrapper script):\nexport DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4          # 1=Mini, 2=Heap, 3=Triage, 4=Full\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/var/dumps/coredump.%p.%t\nmkdir -p /var/dumps\n```\n\nThese tell the CoreCLR runtime to write a dump on unhandled exceptions/crashes.\n\n#### If **NativeAOT**:\n\nNativeAOT has **no built-in managed dump support** — it behaves like a native Linux binary. Use the **kernel core dump** mechanism:\n\n```bash\n# 1. Enable core dumps\nulimit -c unlimited\n\n# 2. Configure the kernel core pattern\nsudo sysctl -w kernel.core_pattern=/var/dumps/core.%e.%p.%t\nsudo mkdir -p /var/dumps\n\n# 3. (Optional) If systemd intercepts cores, configure coredumpctl:\n#    Dumps land in: coredumpctl list\n```\n\n---\n\n### Step 3 — Verify\n\n```bash\n# Send SIGABRT to test (careful — this kills the process!):\nkill -6 12345\n\n# Then check:\nls /var/dumps/\n# Or for systemd: coredumpctl list\n```\n\n**Summary**: Run the `grep libcoreclr` check first. CoreCLR → use `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump`. NativeAOT → use kernel `core_pattern` / `coredumpctl`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d0075401-e7d7-4d1f-8119-10c76e02f0d3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The process doesn't exist on this machine (PID 12345). That's expected — I should guide the user on how to check this themselves and then explain both configuration paths.","outputTokens":697,"requestId":"4182:1EA9D4:649180A:6DD2708:69F164A0"},"id":"ff2495ae-8945-49bb-a018-975c81286aa6","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:53:52.510Z","parentId":"bf433a32-6228-40fa-a58a-c714674a18f8"}
